================================================================================
COMMONS CLAUSE FOR GOVERNMENT PARTNERSHIPS
================================================================================

While this software is provided under the permissive MIT License, users who
modify this software are STRONGLY ENCOURAGED (but not legally required) to:

1. SHARE IMPROVEMENTS: Contribute modifications back to the community,
   especially improvements to:
   - Security features (PKI, RBAC, RLS, Audit logging)
   - Database adapters and performance optimizations
   - Government/public sector specific features
   - Bug fixes and vulnerability patches

2. GOVERNMENT COLLABORATION: Organizations working in the public sector,
   government agencies, or public administration are particularly encouraged
   to share improvements that benefit public infrastructure and transparency.

3. HOW TO CONTRIBUTE:
   - Submit Pull Requests: https://github.com/makr-code/VCC-UDS3/pulls
   - Report Issues: https://github.com/makr-code/VCC-UDS3/issues
   - Contact: ma.krueger@outlook.com

4. RECOGNITION: Organizations that contribute improvements will be recognized
   in the project's CONTRIBUTORS.md file and release notes.

This clause does NOT impose legal obligations beyond the MIT License terms.
It is a request for good faith collaboration in the spirit of open source
and public benefit, particularly for government and administrative software.

Users who choose not to share improvements are still in full compliance with
the MIT License and may use this software without restriction.

================================================================================
RATIONALE
================================================================================

This software is developed with government partnerships and public
administration use cases in mind. Shared improvements help:

- Strengthen security for all public sector users
- Reduce duplicate development efforts across agencies
- Improve transparency and accountability in government IT
- Build trust through collaborative open source development

We believe that software serving the public good benefits most when
improvements are shared openly, while respecting the freedom granted
by the MIT License.

For questions about this Commons Clause, contact: ma.krueger@outlook.com
